\begin_layout Subsubsection
Bootstrap Grid System
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Many web developers have used tables to layout pages.
 Tables made it easier for the web developer, because the developer didn't
 have to worry about either the complexities of CSS, or cross-browser issues.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Unfortunately, while tables may have made it easier for the developer, it
 makes it more of a challenge for both web browsers and accessibility.
 For traditional browsers, complex table structures can degrade the performance
 of page layout.
 For screen readers, tables are read assume tabular data, which may not
 be how the page is actually layed out and designed to be presented to the
 user.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With this in mind, it is never a best practice to do page layout using tables.
 Bootstrap offers a grid system so developers don't feel the urge to layout
 pages using tables.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Bootstrap grid behaves like a table.
 There are rows and columns.
 However, unlike tables, Bootstrap uses CSS to manage the layout of the
 pages.
 In addition, Bootstrap offers support for mobile browsers and different
 sized screens by providing different grids for different screen sizes.
 There are four screensizes provided by Bootstrap grids.
 This allows developers to size content appropriately for various devices.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Grid Notes
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Always 12 columns 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Smaller sizes set the default for larger sizes 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
col-sm- would set the size for small, medium and large screens unless overridden
 by a setting specific to one of the larger sizes 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate-Resume
There is a 30px "gutter", or empty space, between each column (15px on each
 side of the column) 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate-Resume
The gutter on the outside of the container varies based on the current screen
 size 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Extra small devices always use the entire width of the screen
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
